We suspect that a <cluster,drug,time> combination having more cell counts is associated with finding more differentially expressed genes in that combination. Our reasoning is that more cells will increase whatever confidence level we have in a give gene, no matter the actual differential expression value.

Our solution to this is to randomly subsample cells such that each combination will retain an equal number of cells. This analysis will tell us if that is necessary.

Load Data

df = read.csv('DE_cell_sensitivity.csv')
df$gene_fraction = df$gene / 24181

We definitely need to consider DE Direction as a covariate

Linear Model

\(\mu = X\beta\) where \(\mu\) is the number of genes designated differential

m1 = lm(gene ~ cells + de_direction, data = df)

Logistic Model

There is an upper and lower limit to the response variable. It can take on an integer value between zero and the number of genes (24181). It would make sense to model this with logistic regression

\(\text{logit} (\mu) = X\beta\) where \(\mu\) is the fraction of genes designated differential

m2 = glm(gene_fraction ~ cells + de_direction, data = df, family = binomial())
## Warning in eval(family$initialize): non-integer #successes in a binomial glm!

This model tells us the number of cells is NOT statistically significant for the number of DE genes. This is unfortunate because even tho the other 2 models are both generally interpretable, this should theoretically be the most applicable model.

Poisson Model

Since the fraction of genes designated DE comes nowhere close to the upper limit, and since this is integer data (not continuous), Poisson regression also is applicable.

\(\log (\mu) = X\beta\) where \(\mu\) is the number of genes designated differential

m3 = glm(gene ~ cells + de_direction, data = df, family = poisson())
summary(m3)
## 
## Call:
## glm(formula = gene ~ cells + de_direction, family = poisson(),

Residual diagnostics actually looks the best for the Poisson model, so we will adopt it. The number of cells is a significant factor for the number of DE genes. This supports our decision to normalize treatment combinations by cell count.
